Ms. Freeman has been employed with People’s United Bank since 2011 and worked for Northeast Cardiology Associates prior to that time.  Ms. Freeman received her undergraduate degree from the University of Maine and her Masters of Business Administration from Husson University.  She currently serves as Finance Cabinet Chair for United Way of Eastern Maine’s 2013 Campaign, has volunteered for Big Brothers Big Sisters of Mid-Maine, and was a member of the Bangor Region Leadership Institute, Class of 2012.

As a Federally Qualified Health Center (FQHC), PCHC’s Board of Directors serves as its governing body, responsible for financial oversight, strategic planning, defining mission and services, and ensuring compliance with legal and financial requirements, among other responsibilities.";s:10:"post_title";s:47:"Amy Freeman, MBA, Joins PCHC Board of Directors";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:45:"amy-freeman-mba-joins-pchc-board-of-directors";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-09-20 14:16:34";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-09-20 18:16:34";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://www.pchc.com/?p=546";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:12;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"549";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"5";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-06-12 14:16:58";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-12 18:16:58";s:12:"post_content";s:1260:"The Unlimited Solutions Clubhouse recently received a $9,500 grant from the Maine Community Foundation to support food service vocational training for the Clubhouse.  With this grant, Clubhouse members will receive training on food safety, customer service, and other aspects of the food service industry, as well as produce a video of the trainings.  The vocational trainings will greatly help Clubhouse members apply for and successfully obtain food-industry jobs.

“We are very thankful to Maine Community Foundation for providing funding for this great opportunity for our members at Unlimited Solutions,” said Carrie Lemos, Executive Director of Unlimited Solutions Clubhouse. “The members are excited to get started with this training and look forward to gainful employment in the food service industry in the near future.”

Opened in 2012, the Unlimited Solutions Clubhouse is a community of people who are working together to achieve a common goal - recovery from mental illness.  During the course of their participation in the Clubhouse, members gain access to opportunities to rejoin the worlds of friendships, family, employment and education, and to the services and support they may individually need to continue their recovery.";s:10:"post_title";s:51:"Unlimited Solutions Clubhouse Receives $9,500 Grant";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:49:"unlimited-solutions-clubhouse-receives-9500-grant";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-09-20 14:17:47";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-09-20 18:17:47";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://www.pchc.com/?p=549";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:13;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"551";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"5";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-06-05 14:18:37";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-05 18:18:37";s:12:"post_content";s:1021:"Kathleen M. Hayden, Vice President and Branch Manager, Bangor Savings Bank presented members of PCHC's Unlimited Solutions Clubhouse with a check for $1,000 on Friday, May 31<sup>st</sup>. Unlimited Solutions received a high number of write-in votes as part of the Community Matters More Campaign to win the funding.

Carrie Lemos, OTR/L, MHRT-C, Clubhouse Executive Director, states, "Clubhouse members are thrilled to have been selected and are proud to receive this financial support.  The success of our model relies greatly on the support of the community and we are grateful to Bangor Savings Bank and all those who voted for us."

Unlimited Solutions Clubhouse focuses on recovery from mental illness through the use of a therapeutic environment that includes responsibilities within the Clubhouse and outside the Clubhouse.  The model features work and membership as primary methods for providing individuals with opportunities in employment, housing, education, skill development, and social activities.";s:10:"post_title";s:44:"Clubhouse Receives $1000 from Bangor Savings";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:43:"clubhouse-receives-1000-from-bangor-savings";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-09-20 14:20:07";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-09-20 18:20:07";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://www.pchc.com/?p=551";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:14;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"554";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"5";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-05-19 14:20:29";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-19 18:20:29";s:12:"post_content";s:1501:"Renovations of Capehart Community Health Center on 86 Davis Road, Bangor, are underway. The renovations, which are expected to be completed by July 2013, will modernize the facility like several of PCHC’s larger practices, provide upgrades to many life safety systems, and will improve accessibility for patients.

It is anticipated that the project will employ between 50-60 workers at various points of the renovation, all from Maine based companies employing Maine tradespeople.  The companies selected to work on the project participated in a bid process.  The project is managed by Nickerson &amp; O’Day, and will involve a number of local subcontractors, including RJ Morin, Duffy’s Electric, Downeast Sheet Metal, Central Maine Drywall, Hammond Lumber, Streets Landscaping, Maine Fire Protection, Grenier's Classic Flooring &amp; Design, Hussey Painting, Builders Installed Products Inc., Pond Cove Millwork, Kamco Supply, Architectural Doors and Windows, and Bellefleur and Sons Advanced Roofing.

The staff of Capehart Community Health Center is temporarily providing services at 992 Union Street, Bangor, to minimize disruption to patient care.  Hardy Construction, Inc., managed the renovations at their temporary space which involved work by over a dozen people from Hardy Construction and various local subcontractors, including Mike Marquis Mechanical, the Family Floor Store, Newport Glass, Maine Fire Protection, Norris, Inc., Invironments, Inc., and Central Security.";s:10:"post_title";s:42:"Capehart Community Health Center Renovated";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:42:"capehart-community-health-center-renovated";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-09-20 14:21:22";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-09-20 18:21:22";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://www.pchc.com/?p=554";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:15;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"556";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"5";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-05-27 14:23:18";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-27 18:23:18";s:12:"post_content";s:1142:"Penobscot Community Health Care (PCHC) is pleased to welcome esteemed healthcare leader Wendy J. Wolf, M.D., M.P.H., to tonight’s Annual Meeting in Brewer. Dr. Wolf is the founding President and CEO of the Maine Health Access Foundation (MeHAF), the state’s largest private health philanthropy.

For over 13 years, Dr. Wolf has worked hand-in-hand with MeHAF to expand access and improve the health of Maine people, particularly those who are uninsured and undeserved. Dr. Wolf has guided the foundation’s engagement in public policy and positioned the foundation as a leader in Maine’s philanthropic sector. She has authorized numerous scientific publications, and is a nationally recognized speaker on health care policy and professional development. Dr. Wolf currently services on the board of directors for Grantmakers in Health, and services on the Maine Community Foundation Board.

PCHC’s Annual Meeting will take place Tuesday, May 28<sup>th</sup> at 5pm at Brewer Medical Center, located at 735 Wilson Street in Brewer. Dr. Wolf’s keynote is scheduled to begin at 6pm and will focus on the revolution of health care.";s:10:"post_title";s:41:"Dr. Wendy Wolf to Speak at Annual Meeting";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:40:"dr-wendy-wolf-to-speak-at-annual-meeting";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-09-20 14:25:05";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-09-20 18:25:05";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://www.pchc.com/?p=556";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:16;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"559";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"5";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-05-22 14:28:50";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-22 18:28:50";s:12:"post_content";s:3797:"PORTLAND – The City of Portland Minority Health Program in collaboration with the University of New England and Maine AIDS Education and Training Center (MEAETC), a division of Penobscot Community Health Center will host the 3rd Annual Maine Minority Health Conference on Tuesday, June 4, 2013 from 7:00 a.m. – 3:00 p.m. at the University of New England’s Portland Campus at 716 Stevens Avenue.  The theme of the conference is “Health Equity &amp; Accountable Care:  Patients, Populations, and Partnerships” and the conference is free and open to the public

According to conference coordinator Kolawole Bankole, MD, MS, OPIc, who is the Access Project Director/Minority Health Program Coordinator for the City of Portland, Health and Human Services Department,  Public Health Division, the symposium is open to all health care professionals, staff from community-based organizations, patients, clients and anyone interested in the care and treatment of minority patients. The goal of the conference is to provide a forum to present current research, information and trends in health equity and the Affordable Care Act and engage key stakeholders in discussion.

"In order to ensure that the Affordable Care Act is implemented to help reduce health disparities and enhance health equity, people need to be educated about health care reform and its impact on vulnerable minority populations,” said Dr. Bankole.  "This conference is designed to help raise awareness for all stakeholders about service provision and the importance of culturally sensitive health care delivery. This is an important and timely topic given the implementation of the Affordable Care Act beginning in January, 2014.”

Conference highlights will include an opening keynote by Cara V. James, PhD, and John Auerbach, MBA, on “The Affordable Care Act &amp; Its Potential to Reduce Health Disparities;” a program overview of UNE’s CHANNELS project by Jennifer Morton, DNP, MPH, Leslie Brancato, MSW, and Shelley Cohen Konrad, PhD; presentations  on “Local, Population and Consumer Centered Care” by Joseph P. Ditre, Esq. and “Patient-Centered Primary Care” by Sarah Dubay, Med, MMEL; a luncheon keynote by Ann Lemire, MD on “Serving Vulnerable Populations” and a presentation by Pious A. Ali on “Youth and Health Equity.”

The University of New England is the lead partner and venue to host the 3rd Annual Maine Minority Health Conference due to its steadfast commitment to collaboration with community partners and engagement in community health initiatives as demonstrated through its Interprofessional Education, and cross-cultural health initiatives such as the CHANNELS project.

The Portland Public Health Division, part of the City's Health and Human Services Department, is composed of seven programs: Chronic Disease Prevention, Environmental Health and Safety, Family Health, Health Care for the Homeless, Health Equity and Research, India Street Clinical Services, and Operations. The Division provides services from 12 sites throughout the City, but also manages projects that impact public health across Cumberland County and the state of Maine.

MEAETC is providing generous support with funding from the New England AIDS Education and Training Center project, funded by the U.S. Department of HHS, Health Resources and Services Administration.

Registration is required by May 30, 2013 and interested participants may contact Heather Foster at the Maine AIDS Education and Training Center at 207-990-3626 or <a href="mailto:hfoster@pchcbangor.org">hfoster@pchcbangor.org</a>.

For additional information on the Minority Health Conference, contact Kolawole Bankole, MD at 207-874-8773 or <a href="mailto:bak@portlandmaine.gov">bak@portlandmaine.gov</a>.";s:10:"post_title";s:89:"City of Portland and UNE Co-Host 3rd Annual Maine Minority Health Conference June 4, 2013";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:88:"city-of-portland-and-une-co-host-3rd-annual-maine-minority-health-conference-june-4-2013";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-09-20 14:30:07";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-09-20 18:30:07";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://www.pchc.com/?p=559";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:17;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"561";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"5";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-05-16 14:30:36";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-16 18:30:36";s:12:"post_content";s:1358:"Penny Lamhut, MD, has joined the medical staff of PCHC’s Community Care and Geriatrics whose multi provider team serves patients in area nursing homes, rehabilitation facilities, or for in-home visits.  Dr. Lamhut’s practice centers on all aspects of high-quality geriatric medical care, including patient physicals, acute visits, and health care maintenance.

Penny Lamhut, MD, received both her undergraduate and her Medical Degree from McGill University, Montreal, Quebec, Canada.  Prior to joining Penobscot Community Health Care, Dr. Lamhut served as a Geriatrician in private practice.  Robert Allen, MD, PCHC’s Executive Medical Director, states, “PCHC is proud that Penny Lamhut, MD, has joined Community Care and Geriatrics.  Dr. Lamhut is the Medical Director of the Dirigo Pines Retirement Community, is Board Certified in Geriatrics, and is also a Certified Medical Director.  Dr. Lamhut offers an outstanding patient care approach and considerable expertise in Geriatrics.”

Dr. Lamhut is board certified by the American Board of Family Practice and certified as Medical Director by the American Medical Directors Association.  Dr. Lamhut will be seeing patients at area nursing and rehabilitation facilities.  For more information on PCHC’s Community Care &amp; Geriatrics, please call 207-945-5247, extension 598.";s:10:"post_title";s:51:"Penny Lamhut, MD, Joins Community Care & Geriatrics";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:47:"penny-lamhut-md-joins-community-care-geriatrics";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-09-20 14:31:56";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-09-20 18:31:56";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://www.pchc.com/?p=561";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:18;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"564";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"5";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-05-16 14:32:46";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-16 18:32:46";s:12:"post_content";s:534:"The Downeast Association of Physician Assistants (DEAPA) recently honored our very own Ken Nadeau, PA-C, with the Outstanding Maine Physician Assistant Award. This award is presented each year to a Maine Physician Assistant in recognition of dedicated service to the community, both as a health care provider and as a citizen. Ken has consistently gone above and beyond in providing the highest level of care here at PCHC and has inspired others in his field to do the same.

Please join us in congratulating Ken on a job well done!";s:10:"post_title";s:48:"Ken Nadeau, PA-C, Honored with Prestigious Award";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:46:"ken-nadeau-pa-c-honored-with-prestigious-award";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-09-20 14:34:22";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-09-20 18:34:22";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://www.pchc.com/?p=564";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:19;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"567";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"5";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-05-09 14:34:45";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-09 18:34:45";s:12:"post_content";s:1313:"Penobscot Community Health Care (PCHC) is pleased to announce that Lorraine Lick, FNP, has joined the medical staff of PCHC’s Helen Hunt Health Center, 242 Brunswick Street, Old Town. Ms. Lick’s practice centers on all aspects of high-quality medical care, including patient physicals, acute visits, and health care maintenance.

Lorraine Lick, FNP-C, received both her undergraduate and her Master of Science in Nursing Degrees from Washburn University, Topeka, Kansas.  Prior to joining Penobscot Community Health Care, Ms. Lick worked as a Nurse Practitioner in cardiothoracic surgery for an area hospital. Robert Allen, MD, PCHC’s Executive Medical Director, states, “PCHC is pleased that Lorraine Lick, FNP-C, has joined Helen Hunt Health Center.  Lorraine is an excellent, caring, and compassionate provider who brings extensive clinical background in orthopedic and cardiac care.  Patients of Helen Hunt Health Center will enjoy seeing her as their provider.”

Ms. Lick is a member of the American Academy of Nurse Practitioners and is seeing patients at Helen Hunt Health Center; for an appointment please call 827-6128. Helen Hunt Health Center is open seven days per week and in addition to family medical care, offers Walk-In Care, Pharmacy, Physical Therapy, Podiatry, and X-ray.";s:10:"post_title";s:50:"Lorraine Lick, FNP-C, Joins Helen Hunt Health Care";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:48:"lorraine-lick-fnp-c-joins-helen-hunt-health-care";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-09-20 14:36:02";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-09-20 18:36:02";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://www.pchc.com/?p=567";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}}s:8:"col_info";a:23:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:2:"ID";s:5:"table";s:10:"pchc_posts";s:3:"def";s:0:"";s:10:"max_length";i:3;s:8:"not_null";i:1;s:11:"primary_key";i:1;s:12:"multiple_key";i:0;s:10:"unique_key";i:0;s:7:"numeric";i:1;s:4:"blob";i:0;s:4:"type";s:3:"int";s:8:"unsigned";i:1;s:8:"zerofill";i:0;}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:11:"post_author";s:5:"table";s:10:"pchc_posts";s:3:"def";s:0:"";s:10:"max_length";i:1;s:8:"not_null";i:1;s:11:"primary_key";i:0;s:12:"multiple_key";i:1;s:10:"unique_key";i:0;s:7:"numeric";i:1;s:4:"blob";i:0;s:4:"type";s:3:"int";s:8:"unsigned";i:1;s:8:"zerofill";i:0;}i:2;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:9:"post_date";s:5:"table";s:10:"pchc_posts";s:3:"def";s:0:"";s:10:"max_length";i:19;s:8:"not_null";i:1;s:11:"primary_key";i:0;s:12:"multiple_key";i:0;s:10:"unique_key";i:0;s:7:"numeric";i:0;s:4:"blob";i:0;s:4:"type";s:8:"datetime";s:8:"unsigned";i:0;s:8:"zerofill";i:0;}i:3;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:5:"table";s:10:"pchc_posts";s:3: